description.plain:
Death Grips is an experimental multi-genre group from Sacramento, CA, formed in 2010. Their music and live performances consist of vocals from Stefan “MC Ride” Burnett and production from Zach Hill and Andy Morin. They released their first mixtape, Exmilitary on April 25, 2011, with their most popular song, Guillotine, on that project. Early in the following year, they signed to Epic Records, and released their first studio album, The Money Store. They teased their second studio album via an ARG in August of that year, but Epic didn’t want them to release the album yet. They did anyway, leaking it themselves, naming it No Love Deep Web, and getting dropped from Epic as a result. They started their own label in 2013, called Third Worlds, and surprise-released Government Plates on November 13 of that year. June 8, 2014 saw the release of the first half of The Powers That B  On July 2nd, 2014, the band officially announced their disbanding via a note on their Facebook page, but promised the second half of The Powers That B to be released. It leaked as Jenny Death on March 19, 2015, and the entire album was released officially on the 31st. On October 21, 2015, they announced they ‘might make some more’ music together, and released a new album, Bottomless Pit in 2016. Their latest album, Year of the Snitch, was released in 2018.

The band’s music has been described as punk rock, hip-hop, noise, industrial, and electronic. Their sound ranges from minimalistic and trunk-rattling heaviness (such as on “No Love”), to rapping about dark subjects over heavily distorted samples (like on “I’ve Seen Footage”). They have also released two entirely instrumental albums, Fashion Week and Interview 2016, which feature abrasive and violent electronic beats and some guitars.

Frontman Stefan Burnett’s violent lyrics draw inspiration from a struggle both against himself and against the world at large, focusing on themes of individualism, paranoia, mental illness, drug use, occultism, and the emotionally degenerative nature of modern society.

songs.title: Beware

description.plain:
Beware follows an unnamed protagonist as he abandons his humanity, giving in to the anger and frustration in his mind and becoming a sort of monster among men.

The song explores several, admittedly dark, themes, including: sacrifice, satanism, violence, intolerance, greed, rage, witchcraft and magick, and suicide.

The introduction notably samples from an interview with American criminal Charles Manson seen here.

songs.title: Hacker

description.plain:
“Hacker” is the closer to Death Grips' 2012 studio debut The Money Store and the culmination of the entire album. It’s described as “the moment when all shit breaks loose and all that’s left to do is riot.”

In it, he throws out references to several pop culture icons, including Apple, Lady Gaga, and Sammy Davis alongside boasts about his gang and their ability to take on everything.

Ultimately, despite seeming to be another murder anthem, Hacker is MC Ride’s way of telling the world that he and his friends have made their mark and are now a force in the game that you can’t ignore; many lines in the song have a double meaning that relates to the success of the rap group. They’re in your area, on the charts, and can reach anyone they want.

In early 2020, Anthony Fantano rated this song as the best song of the 2010s decade.

songs.title: No Love

description.plain:
Dark, angry, hellish, psychotic, and hypnotic, “No Love” is incredibly intense. Punctuated by a droning electronic churn and  methodical, hard-hitting drums, the song is an example of MC Ride performing at his most lyrically violent and emotionally chaotic.

Some speculate that this song has a double meaning, evident by the lyrics exploring torturing someone (maybe Ride himself) and a bad trip on acid. The hook is both the voice of the drug in MC Ride’s brain and the voice of Ride in the listener’s, as his music sends us on a ‘bad trip’ of our own. Additionally, the music video for the song is displayed in a non-functional 3D anaglyph, showing two simultaneous images that visually hint at the idea of duality.

songs.title: I’ve Seen Footage

description.plain:
Probably the most “accessible” song on the album, MC Ride feels that the stuff he has seen in the ghetto is so messed up that he has detached himself from it and sees it as a dream or video footage and not real.

MC Ride is also describing the amount of disturbing shit you can watch online: videos of decapitations, police brutality, etc. He’s become desensitized not just by the stuff he’s seen in real life, but by the “footage” he’s seen online.

In a 2012 Pitchfork interview, Zach explained the phrase from the title and how the hook came about:

The line “I’ve Seen Footage” was from a conversation I had with this street-person dude in Sacramento named Snake Eyes. A friend of ours recorded him on the porch in a conversation– he didn’t know he was being recorded. He was all fucked up on drugs and shit, just rattling off all this crazy information. He was talking about structures on the moon. I mean, I talk about those things, too. So we were talking about moon structures, and Snake Eyes says, “I’ve seen footage! I’ve seen footage of it!” And I was like, “That’s good!”

description.plain:
As with many Death Grips songs, this one has multiple meanings, many of which are up for interpretation, but the main message is that Death Grips is quickly becoming a dominant force in the rap game. This is one of the few times that Death Grips bothers with a common hip hop subject.

This was the first Death Grips track to feature a guest vocalist, and excluding the Björk vocals sampled throughout Niggas On the Moon, there would not be a feature on a Death Grips song for five years, concluding with the release of “Giving Bad People Good Ideas” on Bottomless Pit.

This track is notably also the first use of a sample from Blue Devils' “The Ditty”, a common sample in Death Grips' work.

songs.title: Birds

description.plain:
“Birds” first appeared on August 21, 2013, and was the first new Death Grips song after they were dropped from their label and decided to just not show up to some of their shows. “Birds” was later included on their third LP, Government Plates, which was spontaneously announced and released for free on November 13, 2013.

A year later, when Government Plates was given its first proper physical release (on vinyl, no less), it was revealed that guitar on this song was played by actor Robert Pattinson, best known as the main vampire guy from the Twilight film franchise. Pattinson and Death Grips have a bit of history together; there were rumors that the actor had appeared in a film directed by Death Grips drummer Zach Hill, and they were earlier seen in a photo together along with Beyoncé, because nothing is out of the realm of possibility with Death Grips.

songs.title: Eh

description.plain:
“Eh” is an ode to apathy. It’s about the struggle to find meaning, focusing on the distinction between genuine human emotion and the contrived nature of fame and celebrity.

Wild but soft synths and subtle drums support Ride’s comparatively tame vocals and highlight the apathetic theming. The song’s wholly electronic production sits in contrast to some of the guitar-driven tracks on the album like “Ring A Bell” and “Giving Bad People Good Ideas,” and harkens back to the equally electronic No Love Deep Web.

“Eh” premiered on Zane Lowe’s Beats 1 radio show as the “World Record” feature on May 5, 2016, acting as Bottomless Pit’s 3rd single.

description.plain:
One of Death Grips' most lyrically straightforward songs, “Punk Weight” is an ode to violence and a proclamation of constant forward motion. High-pitched, accelerated vocals abruptly segue into overblown blasts of distorted drums and wailing synth stabs.

The song also draws attention to the Stefan’s use of Ride’s monstrous characterization to display an unruly punk ideology:

There are characters in [punk] that do deliberately go as far as they can in certain kind of taboo areas.
- Richard Hell
